helpdesk-ticket.subject: Remote Access
helpdesk-ticket.description:
Good evening.
I am a new faculty member and I funny got access to everything I need (I think) while on campus. However, while attempting to login from home this weekend, I found that I cannot access Outlook, or any of my drives (H:, M:, and O:). Do I need to use VPN to get remote access to these drives and, if so, how do I get the correct software?
Second, I tried logging into Office 365 using my normal user login, and that didn't work either. For some reason, my password was not recognized.
Finally, I will need access to MATLAB for one of the courses I am teaching, ME 230. How do I get access to this software?
I need to get these issues ironed out as quickly as possible because I am working at my current job through August and I cannot be on campus until after that point.
Please let me know what I need to do to get the correct access.
Thank you.
Rick Dykowski
Sent by Outlook<http://taps.io/outlookmobile> for Android

Second, I tried logging into Office 365 using my normal user login, and that didn't work either. For some reason, my password was not recognized.
Finally, I will need access to MATLAB for one of the courses I am teaching, ME 230. How do I get access to this software?

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Richard Dykowski,
Are you using an MSOE issued machine? If so, you should have Global Protect VPN installed on your machine. Once you are connected to VPN you will be able to access network drives. To download software, you will need to go into Programs and Features from the Control Panel and select Install Programs from the Netowrk on the left hand side. You should be able to download MATLAB from there. Please keep in mind you will only be able to download the software if you are connected to VPN or if you are on campus.
Are you trying to access your email via Office365? If so you need to go to outlook.com/msoe.edu and from there you will be able to access your email from there.
Please let me know if you have any further questions.
Thanks, Shawna
Ticket: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/54

helpdesk-ticket.subject: Xbox one strict NAT
helpdesk-ticket.description:
Hello,
I recently purchased an Xbox one, and I live in the grohmann tower. I am unable to play online games due to a strict NAT type. I've contacted Xbox customer support, and I've tried all of their suggestions. I've reset UPnP on my router, tried setting up DMZ, tried port forwarding on a static IP address, reset my router to factory defaults, and I am still seeing a strict NAT on my Xbox which doesn't allow me to use the Xbox's online features. Is there anything that IT can do to resolve this issue, or offer any suggestions that might fix my issue? For reference, the router I am using in my room is a netgear WNR1000v3.
Thank you,
Scott Connors

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi connorss, Ticket: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/56 The transmission protocol that the XBO uses is called Teredo. It allows use of IPv6 over IPv4 networks. However, the MSOE network does not support IPv6 traffic. IPv6 traffic will fail back to IPv4 when it cannot establish a connection. The dorm rooms in Grohmann Tower also each have an internet-routable IP address that does not use NAT. If you are using a switch or router in your room, it may introduce NAT (typically 192.168.0.0). I suggest connecting the XBO directly to the wall jack, using MSOE Wireless (Not MSOE-Guest, as it is heavily limited) or if you are using a router, set the IP of the XBO to the DMZ on the router.
Chances are, due to the inability to negotiate Teredo, you will always get a limited NAT warning, but you should not experience any issues.
Thanks,
Paul Fabian MSOE Network Admin
helpdesk-note.body-html:
Hi connorss,

Ticket: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/56

The transmission protocol that the XBO uses is called Teredo. It allows use of IPv6 over IPv4 networks. However, the MSOE network does not support IPv6 traffic. IPv6 traffic will fail back to IPv4 when it cannot establish a connection. The dorm rooms in Grohmann Tower also each have an internet-routable IP address that does not use NAT. If you are using a switch or router in your room, it may introduce NAT (typically 192.168.0.0). I suggest connecting the XBO directly to the wall jack, using MSOE Wireless (Not MSOE-Guest, as it is heavily limited) or if you are using a router, set the IP of the XBO to the DMZ on the router.

Chances are, due to the inability to negotiate Teredo, you will always get a limited NAT warning, but you should not experience any issues.

Thanks,

Paul Fabian
MSOE Network Admin

From: Helpdesk Sent: Thursday, August 13, 2015 4:54 PM To: All Faculty; All Staff Subject: Information Technology Updates
[cid:image001.png@01D0D9CB.F333EF80]
In an attempt to improve our support to faculty, staff and students we are making the following changes. Walk Up Services – Now in 3rd Floor CC Building We have moved! The Helpdesk is now located in the 3rd Floor of the CC building in an effort to be centralized for all students to access our services. Our hours of operation both during the school year and summer/break week have not changed. New Ticketing Tool - FreshService Beginning August 20, the IT Department will be implementing a new way to handle your requests. We have heard of the shortcomings of using SchoolDude for IT requests and have researched better tools to serve you. From that research, we will be utilizing a tool called FreshService. The benefits of FreshService include:
1. No need to log in to create a ticket.
2. No password required to create a ticket.
3. The ability to create a ticket just by sending an email.
4. A mobile app available to submit a ticket from wherever you are. (available in Google and Apple app stores)
5. A dashboard tool for IT to better track and respond to tickets in a timely manner. We have reactivated the ability to email us at helpdesk@msoe.edu<mailto:helpdesk@msoe.edu>. This will be the easiest way to reach the IT department. If you would like to create an account to view updates to your tickets, please go to http://helpdesk.msoe.edu (starting August 20).
Please feel free to contact the Helpdesk with any support questions or issues you may have. No MSOE employees nor any MSOE correspondence will ever ask you for your account password.

From: Helpdesk
Sent: Thursday, August 13, 2015 4:54 PM
To: All Faculty; All Staff
Subject: Information Technology Updates
 
 
 
In an attempt to improve our support to faculty, staff and students we are making the following changes.

Walk Up Services – Now in 3rd Floor CC Building

We have moved! The Helpdesk is now located in the 3rd Floor of the CC building in an effort to be centralized for all students to access our services. Our hours of operation both during the school year and summer/break week have not changed.

New Ticketing Tool - FreshService

Beginning August 20, the IT Department will be implementing a new way to handle your requests. We have heard of the shortcomings of using SchoolDude for IT requests and have researched better tools to serve you. From that research, we will be utilizing a tool called FreshService.
The benefits of FreshService include:
1.       No need to log in to create a ticket.
2.       No password required to create a ticket.
3.       The ability to create a ticket just by sending an email.
4.       A mobile app available to submit a ticket from wherever you are. (available in Google and Apple app stores)
5.       A dashboard tool for IT to better track and respond to tickets in a timely manner.
We have reactivated the ability to email us at helpdesk@msoe.edu. This will be the easiest way to reach the IT department.
If you would like to create an account to view updates to your tickets, please go to http://helpdesk.msoe.edu (starting August 20).
 
Please feel free to contact the Helpdesk with any support questions or issues you may have.
No MSOE employees nor any MSOE correspondence will ever ask you for your account password.
 
 
Information Technology (IT)

414-277-7288

helpdesk-note.body: i went over there and looked at the unit. I suspected that office was activated or something of the sort, but it appears to be a greater local permissions issue. All of the required unix groups and permissions are there on the machine but its still not allowing word doc to be saved or viewed. I checked the permissions levels of the admin account and they have full sudo and the certificates and credentials for office and several other not working apps. helpdesk-ticket.subject: Submit picture - MSOE ID
helpdesk-ticket.description:
Before August 28th, you have the option of submitting the photo of your choice to be used for your MSOE ID Card.
Pictures must adhere to the following standards:
> Frame the subject with full face, front view, eyes open.
> No hats, sunglasses or any items that obstruct the view of your face.
> No other people or objects in photo.
> Photo must include your full head from top of your hair to bottom of your chin.
> Photo must be a color photograph with plain white or off-white background.
> Position subject and lighting so there are no distracting shadows on the face or background.
> Subject must have a natural expression.
> Only .JPEG images are accepted. NO PNG files.
[cid:image001.jpg@01D0DB3D.6432C040]
WEBCARD CENTER:
Webcard Center can be used once you have a network username/password for MSOE.
https://webcard.msoe.edu
Login: MSOE network username / MSOE password
If you are off campus, you must use the MSOE SSLVPN (Instructions are on The Hub (www.msoe.edu<http://www.msoe.edu>).
Once logged in, go to Notification Preferences and provide an email and/or cell phone number. Then select a type of instant alert for each option, including one for Photo Upload, save, then click Submit ID Photo and upload the photo.
Upload Photo: Select a photo you would like to submit for approval. The crop option screen will appear. Make sure you are facing forward, crop just above head, side, lower neck areas. Submit.
Your MSOE ID Card will be available on Faculty In-Service Day, SEPTEMBER 2, 2015.
If you have any questions about these instructions, please e-mail Sheila Barber: barber@msoe.edu<mailto:barber@msoe.edu>
If you have any questions related to In-Service, please e-mail: miller@msoe.edu<mailto:miller@msoe.edu>
Thank you. We look forward to welcoming you back to campus on September 2nd.
Sue Miller
Academics
miller@msoe.edu<mailto:miller@msoe.edu>

helpdesk-ticket.subject: Bad disk
helpdesk-ticket.description: HP Elitebook 8570w reports a bad disk at port 0 - the main hard drive I'm pretty sure. I'm wondering if IT will replace it. I have backed up all data including a Windows 7 boot disk and an image on an external hard drive. I am a grad student. Laptop return year 2015. Laptop issued 2013. Laptop ID 00034787 If you don't offer to replace it or otherwise fix it I will simply buy a replacement hard-drive and switch them out. I'll make sure that's an ok thing to do. The Intel software gives me an error that indicates slow degradation over time, indicating that this is a hardware problem and not software. The error appears on the desktop but also at boot. I tried a restore to factory state through the boot menu but near the end of the process when it was re-installing windows it reported the error again. Other information you might like: HP Hardware Diagnostics UEFI: Version 1.6.0.0 - BIOS Memory test passed Extensive hard drive check - failed immediately Error 60FFXU-1N07P5-MFKSXG-60F603 Product ID: A2X01AV Hard Drive:1 Via the Intel software: SATA disk at risk Port 0 Serial TF0400Y1O8LKBJ Model HGST HTS725032A7E630 Firmware GHBOA440

We are pleased to announce an update to the printing services offered on our campus. Over the course of the next few weeks, we will be changing over from Follow You Printing on Morpheus to Follow you Printing on Printers.
During a review of current technologies, we have found that card swipes mounted next to the printers were old and becoming difficult to replace. helpdesk-ticket.subject: Activating MATLAB
helpdesk-ticket.description:
Good evening.
I just downloaded MATLAB using VPN as instructed, but it is now asking me for an activation key. How do I obtain this information?
Thank you.
Rick Dykowski
helpdesk-ticket.description-html:
Good evening.
 
I just downloaded MATLAB using VPN as instructed, but it is now asking me for an activation key. How do I obtain this information?
 
Thank you.
 
Rick Dykowski

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Richard Dykowski, Ticket: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/131
The installation process for Matlab R2015a under the school's get program list is an automated process. While wired in on the network on campus the automated process goes by in about a second. My suspicion with this issue is that maybe by going through Global Protect and installing the program from an off campus network this automated process slows down to a point where it seems like it is no longer automated. I tested this and for me from the time I clicked install until when the automated process finished took about 15 minutes.
I want you to give this another try. Make sure you are connected to MSOE's network through global protect and once you click install wait before you click anything else. Allow the program at least 20 minutes to at least get to the % until complete bar. Moreover allow at least 90 minutes for the whole process to finish.
**Please note that if you have any version of Matlab on your computer you must uninstall it before re installing a new version.**
If you have any questions my desk phone number is 414-277-2235
Best, Sam West MSOE IT - Assistant Systems Admin

helpdesk-note.body:
Laptop exchange will be held on Tuesday, September 1st from 11am until 8pm in the CC building on the 2nd floor. It takes up the whole open space on the second floor, you will not miss it. As a returning student, you can come anytime. Exchanges will not be accepted at the Help Desk, only on the 2nd floor. If you cannot make it to town on Tuesday the 1st, we will also be hosting an exchange Sept 8-10 from 9am-3pm in the Multipurpose Room located in the great room of the C building 3rd floor. Make sure to back up all your data and to remove any stickers or extra hardware you may have added (RAM, wireless mouse, etc.). Once the machine is turned in, it is not coming back.
The Help Desk is on summer hours during Welcome Week. Academic hours start on the first day of classes, Sept 8.
I will consider this request resolved at this time.
Ticket: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/170 Peter Pfister Help Desk Coordinator 414.277.7202

helpdesk-note.body-html: I was able to find the way we mapped drives last time to get them visible.  Sheila

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Sheila, Click on the Windows button in the lower left hand corner then left click on computer. Then click on the "Map network drive" button in the top toolbar.
For the O:\ drive, choose the drive to be O:. Enter \\filestore.msoe.edu\Department in the folder box. Finally, click finish. For the H:\ drive, choose the drive letter to be H:. Enter \\homestore\homedrives$\(username) in the folder box. Click finish.
The drives will then be remapped and should be available. If you have any more issues please respond back to the ticket.
Thanks, Kevin Erl
Ticket: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/179
helpdesk-note.body-html:

For the H:\ drive, choose the drive letter to be H:. Enter \\homestore\homedrives$\(username) in the folder box. Click finish.

The drives will then be remapped and should be available. If you have any more issues please respond back to the ticket.

Thanks,
Kevin Erl

helpdesk-note.body: Sam that 0x0000052e error is caused when the credentials saved on the local computer don't match those on the print server. Its basically a bad username and password error. I hope that helps
helpdesk-note.body-html: Sam that 0x0000052e error is caused when the credentials saved on the local computer don't match those on the print server. Its basically a bad username and password error. I hope that helps

helpdesk-note.body:
Yeah I saw that online too. I found a work around for this. I am going to test it out real quick. Any input?
2. Store a trusted credential in Credential Manager. To do this, follow these steps:
1) In Control Panel, open Credential Manager. 2) Click Add a Windows credential. 3) In the dialog box, enter an appropriate print server name. Then, enter a user name and password that are trusted on the print server. 4) Click OK.

Ok Leah I found a work around for you. I just tested this so it should work!
 
  1. Make sure you are connected through global protect.
  2. Go to the start menu and in the search box type in "Credential Manager".
  3. Click Add a windows credential. 
  4. In the first box type in printers.msoe.edu.
  5. For a username use ruplingerl, and your password should be your current password for msoe.edu. 
  6. Click ok and go ahead and try and connect to follow you printing on printers.msoe.edu

helpdesk-ticket.subject: Tower Firewall Policy
helpdesk-ticket.description:
Hey Paul,
I hope summer is treating you well. I just moved into the Tower at the beginning of August. In the interest of completing my home theater setup, I plan on building a HTPC and using it in tandem with a NAS unit. Most times, I would only need to access the NAS from within the apartment or elsewhere in the Tower anyway, but one of the best features would be having file access back home and in other locations.
My big question is... with the way the MSOE firewall is setup (to block outside connections), would I be able to connect to a personal NAS in my apartment from, say, Racine, WI? If not, is it possible to get an IP-specific exception for the room so I can do it? (I also may want to host a gaming server in the near future, and as I found out last year, it runs into the same issue as I suspect the NAS would.)
Thanks, and I look forward to hearing from you soon,
- Cody Haws Software Engineering Class of 2018

I hope summer is treating you well. I just moved into the Tower at the beginning of August. In the interest of completing my home theater setup, I plan on building a HTPC and using it in tandem with a NAS unit. Most times, I would only need to access the NAS from within the apartment or elsewhere in the Tower anyway, but one of the best features would be having file access back home and in other locations.
 
My big question is... with the way the MSOE firewall is setup (to block outside connections), would I be able to connect to a personal NAS in my apartment from, say, Racine, WI? If not, is it possible to get an IP-specific exception for the room so I can do it? (I also may want to host a gaming server in the near future, and as I found out last year, it runs into the same issue as I suspect the NAS would.)
 
Thanks, and I look forward to hearing from you soon,
 
- Cody Haws
Software Engineering
Class of 2018

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi hawsc, Ticket: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/200 I'm sorry, we do block most outbound connections leaving or entering the MSOE network. There isn't any way for you to reach your NAS from outside the MSOE network. As a policy we do not do static IP, DMZ, or port forwarding for residents. The same applies for the game server. However the game sever and NAS will work within the MSOE network. Sorry for the inconvenience.
MSOE Information Technology Cameron Wilson

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi hawsc, Ticket: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/200 Cody,
The firewall will allow any outbound connection to the internet (the Untrusted zone), but as you mentioned, it will block unsolicited inbound connections from Untrust. You can use the GlobalProtect VPN client to open a connection to campus IP addresses, but you'd need to use a service like DynDNS to manage an IP address that may change. We don't usually assign static IP addresses in the dorms, as we don't want to encourage private servers hosting files for which the university is liable, or at the risk of finding our IP range on a blacklist. The alternative would be a dedicated server offsite that clients can connect to independent of the university network.
If this all seems a bit like antiquated thinking, you'd be right. We'd like to be able to allow students, particularly the ones in the Tower, personal accountability for their own services. We're still early in the planning phases for services in the Tower as we're on the City of Milwaukee's timeline for permits and approvals. We'd like to reissue a new Acceptable Use Policy that would give both the university and the students more flexibility and responsibility for their services. I don't know that either of these things will happen this year.
That being said, should you reach the point where you're hosting your own server with your own security and the university's security in mind, and you run into issues, I'd be happy to revisit issuing a static IP and firewall policy to your room.
Thanks,
Paul Fabian MSOE Director of IT Services fabian@msoe.edu (414) 277-2355

You can use the GlobalProtect VPN client to open a connection to campus IP addresses, but you'd need to use a service like DynDNS to manage an IP address that may change. We don't usually assign static IP addresses in the dorms, as we don't want to encourage private servers hosting files for which the university is liable, or at the risk of finding our IP range on a blacklist. The alternative would be a dedicated server offsite that clients can connect to independent of the university network.

If this all seems a bit like antiquated thinking, you'd be right. We'd like to be able to allow students, particularly the ones in the Tower, personal accountability for their own services. We're still early in the planning phases for services in the Tower as we're on the City of Milwaukee's timeline for permits and approvals. We'd like to reissue a new Acceptable Use Policy that would give both the university and the students more flexibility and responsibility for their services. I don't know that either of these things will happen this year.

That being said, should you reach the point where you're hosting your own server with your own security and the university's security in mind, and you run into issues, I'd be happy to revisit issuing a static IP and firewall policy to your room.

helpdesk-ticket.subject: Tower Apartment Ethernet port activation
helpdesk-ticket.description: RIck Gagliano needs the ethernet ports in the living room of apartment 1409 in the Tower to be activated. He says the port(s) in the bedroom have been activated, just not the living room.
helpdesk-ticket.description-html: RIck Gagliano needs the ethernet ports in the living room of apartment 1409 in the Tower to be activated. He says the port(s) in the bedroom have been activated, just not the living room.

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi gagliano, Ticket: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/247 Rick,
As discussed in the past, the design of the rooms, and the wiring done by the contractors only allows for one port per room number to be active. Each suite/room number was only wired to the closet on one port. This was an early design and cost decision in the initial stages of the Tower project. This applies to all accommodations on all floors of the Tower; both new and old construction. In old construction, the other wall ports are for phones, not network.
Each room number will only have one live network port. It cannot be moved. The understanding was that students would use the robust and more cost-effective wireless installed on each floor.
Thanks

If you have any issues or the problem persists please do not hesitate to respond to this ticket or call the helpdesk.
Thanks,
Kevin Erl Ticket: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/254

helpdesk-ticket.subject: Outlook issues after changing passwords.
helpdesk-ticket.description:
Hi Liz,
I'm sorry to hear about the issues with outlook. Could you try a few steps for me?
1. Close the Outlook desktop application 2. Click on the start menu orb in the lower left hand corner 3. Type in "Credential Manager" 4. In the bottom of Credential Manager where it says "Generic Credentials", click on the credential starting with "MS.Outlook:..." 5. Click on the "Remove from Vault" button 6. Select "Yes" when you are prompted if you would like to remove the credential. 7. Open Outlook. It should now prompt you for adding your new password.
If you have any more issues after these steps please do not hesitate to respond or to call the helpdesk again at (414)-277-7288. Thanks,
Kevin
helpdesk-ticket.description-html:
Hi Liz,

I'm sorry to hear about the issues with outlook. Could you try a few steps for me?

1. Close the Outlook desktop application
2. Click on the start menu orb in the lower left hand corner
3. Type in "Credential Manager"
4. In the bottom of Credential Manager where it says "Generic Credentials", click on the credential starting with "MS.Outlook:..."
5. Click on the "Remove from Vault" button
6. Select "Yes" when you are prompted if you would like to remove the credential.
7. Open Outlook. It should now prompt you for adding your new password.

If you have any more issues after these steps please do not hesitate to respond or to call the helpdesk again at (414)-277-7288.
Thanks,

Kevin

helpdesk-note.body: Hi Steve, You should be able to print to the papercut system over VPN. The setup for personal computers is the same as with the MSOE laptop. First, hit the windows key and r at the same time. Type in the address of \\printers.msoe.edu. You will then be prompted for a username in password. For the username put in MSOE\username and for the password put in your MSOE password. Finally, double click on Follow you Printing. Is there anything else I can help you with today?
